  <subsection><title>One-Half</title>

    <p>The most familiar fraction is <m>\large{\blert{\text{one-half}}}~~~</m>, or <m>\large{\blert{\dfrac{1}{2}}}.</m></p>

    <image source="half.png" width="55%"></image>

    <p>To find one-half of something, we divide it into <m>\large{\blert{2}}~\blert{\text{equal}}~~</m> pieces and take <m>\large{\blert{1}}</m> of them.

    <me>\large{\dfrac{1}{2}}~~~~~~ \text{means}~~~~~~ \dfrac{\text{take}~~~ \large{1}~~ \text{piece}}{\text{from} ~~~ \large{2}~~ \text{equal pieces}}</me></p>

    <p>If we have a group of objects, we separate them into <m>\large{\blert{2}}~~\blert{\text{equal}}~~</m> groups and take <m>\large{\blert{1}}</m> group.  Each group is a part of the whole.  We write this as a fraction like this:

    <me>\frac{\text{number of objects in the}~\blert{\text{part}}}{\text{number of objects in the}~\blert{\text{whole}}},~~~~\text{or just}~~~~\frac{\large{\blert{\text{part}}}}{\large{\blert{\text{whole}}}}</me></p>

    <example><statement><p><ol marker="a">
        <li><p><m>{\dfrac{1}{2}}</m> of a dozen eggs (12 eggs) <m>=</m> 6 eggs</p>
      
      <image source="eggs.png" width="75%"><description>eggs</description></image>
      
      <m>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\blert{\text{A whole dozen is 12 eggs.}~~~~~~~~~~~~\text{Our part is 6 eggs:} ~~\dfrac{6}{12}}</m>
          <me>\frac{\text{part}}{\text{whole}} = \large{\dfrac{6}{12}} = \large{\dfrac{1}{2}}~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~</me></li>

        <li><p><m>{\dfrac{1}{2}}</m> of an hour (60 minutes) <m>=</m> 30 minutes</p> 
      
      <image source="clocks.png" width="65%"><description>clocks</description></image>
      
      <m>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\blert{\text{A whole hour is 60 minutes.}~~~~~~~~~~\text{Our part is 30 minutes:} ~~\dfrac{30}{60}}</m>
          <me>\frac{\text{part}}{\text{whole}} = \large{\dfrac{30}{60}} = \large{\dfrac{1}{2}}~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~</me></li>
      </ol></p></statement></example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection><title>Other Ways to Write One-Half</title>
    
    <p>From the Example above, we see that <m>{\dfrac{6}{12}}</m> and <m>{\dfrac{30}{60}}</m> are different ways to write <m>{\dfrac{1}{2}}</m>.  Here are some more ways:
      <image source="halves.png" width="60%"><description>eggs</description></image></p>
<m>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\blert{\dfrac{2}{4}~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\dfrac{3}{6}~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\dfrac{4}{8}}</m>

  <exercise><statement><p><ol marker="a">
