<subsection><title>Other Ways to Write Fourths</title>

<p>Earlier we saw that we can write one-half in many different ways. For example,

  <me>\large{\blert{\dfrac{1}{2}=\dfrac{3}{6}=\dfrac{4}{8}}}</me>
  
  We can also write one-fourth and three-fourths in different ways.</p>

  <example><statement><p><ol marker="a">
    <li><p><m>\dfrac{1}{2}</m> of a dozen eggs (12 eggs) <m>=</m> 3 eggs</p>
          
        <image source="three-eggs.png" width="60%"><description>clocks</description></image>
          
        <m>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\blert{\text{A whole dozen is 12 eggs.}~~~~~~~~\text{Our part is 3 eggs:} ~~\dfrac{3}{12}}</m>

        <me>\frac{\text{part}}{\text{whole}} = \large{\dfrac{3}{12}} = \large{\dfrac{1}{4}}~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~</me></li>
    
    <li><p><m>{\dfrac{3}{4}}</m> of an hour (60 minutes) <m>=</m> 45 minutes</p>
          
          <image source="clocks2.png" width="60%"><description>clocks</description></image>  
      
      <m>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\blert{\text{A whole hour is 60 minutes.}~~~~~~~~\text{Our part is 45 minutes:} ~~\dfrac{45}{60}}</m>
          
          <me>\frac{\text{part}}{\text{whole}} = \large{\dfrac{45}{60}} = \large{\dfrac{3}{4}}~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~</me></li>
      </ol></p></statement></example>

  <p>When we write a fraction, the number that gives the "part" (the top) is called the <term>numerator</term>, and the number that gives the "whole" (the bottom) is called the <term>denominator</term>. For example, in the fraction <m>\dfrac{15}{60}</m>, the numerator is 15 and the denominator is 60.

    <me>\frac{\text{part}}{\text{whole}} = \large{\dfrac{15}{60}} = \large{\alert{\dfrac{\text{numerator}}{\text{denominator}}}}</me></p>

    <assemblage><title>Definition</title>
    <p>The <term>denominator</term> of a fraction (the bottom) tells us how many pieces are in one whole. The <term>numerator</term> (the top) tells us how many pieces are in the part.</p></assemblage>

    <note><p>Although it has a different numerator and denominator, the fraction <m>\dfrac{15}{60}</m> is the same as <m>\dfrac{1}{4}</m>,  because 15 pieces are one-fourth of 60 pieces. Both fractions give the same portion of one whole.

      <image source="gridsixty.png" width="40%"><description>grid-fourth</description></image></p></note>

