<subsection><title>Fractions on a Number Line</title>
<p>In the previous exercise we used grids to illustrate fractions. We can also show fractions of a distance on a <term>number line</term>.</p>

<example><statement><p>Mark the fractions <m>\dfrac{1}{2}</m>, <m>\dfrac{1}{4}</m>, and <m>\dfrac{3}{4}</m> of 12 on the number line below.

  <image source="numberline12.png" width="70%"><description>number line</description></image></p></statement>

<solution><p>To find <m>\dfrac{1}{2}</m> of 12, we divide by 2:
              <me>\dfrac{1}{2}~ \text{of}~ 12 = 12 \div 2 = \alert{6}</me></p>
    
    <p>To find <m>\dfrac{1}{4}</m> of 12, we divide by 4:
              <me>\dfrac{1}{4}~ \text{of}~ 12 = 12 \div 4 = \alert{3}</me></p>
    
    <p>To find <m>\dfrac{3}{4}</m> of 12, we multiply <m>\dfrac{1}{4}</m> of 12 by 3:
              <me>\dfrac{3}{4}~ \text{of}~ 12 = 3 \times 3 = \alert{9}</me></p>

<p>Here is a number line showing the results:
  
  <image source="fourthsnumberline.png" width="75%"><description>number line</description></image></p>
</solution></example>

<note><p>From the previous Example, we see that 
  
  <me>\dfrac{1}{4}=\dfrac{3}{12},~~~~  \dfrac{1}{2}=\dfrac{6}{12},~~~~ \text{and} ~~~~  \dfrac{3}{4}=\dfrac{9}{12}</me>

A number line can help us visualize familiar fractions written with different denominators.  Here is the number line from that Example, showing the fractions written with denominator 12.
  <image source="twelfthsnumberline.png" width="75%"><description>number line</description></image></p></note>

