<subsection><title>Benchmark Fractions</title>
<p>The fractions <m>\dfrac{1}{2}</m>, <m>\dfrac{1}{4}</m>, and <m>\dfrac{3}{4}</m> are called <term>benchmark fractions</term> because we have a good intuitive feel for their size. We can estimate other fractions by comparing them to the benchmarks.</p>

<example><statement><p>Of the 32 students in Ethan's math class, 9 are from out-of-state.</p>  <ol marker="a">
  <li><p>What fraction of Ethan's class is from out-of-state?</p></li>
  <li><p>Is that fraction closer to <m>\dfrac{1}{2}</m>, <m>\dfrac{1}{4}</m>, or to <m>\dfrac{3}{4}</m> of the class?</p></li>
</ol></statement>

<solution> <ol marker="a">
  <li><p> We write the fraction as
    
    <me>\dfrac{\text{part}}{\text{whole}} = \dfrac{9~~ \text{out-of-state students}}{32~~ \text{total students}}</me>
  
  Out-of-state students make up <m>\dfrac{9}{32}</m> of Ethan's class.</p></li>
  
  <li><p>Let's compute the benchmark fractions with denominator 32.
      <me>\dfrac{1}{4}~~\text{of}~~32 = 8,~~~~~~~~~~\text{so}~~\dfrac{1}{4}=\dfrac{8}{32}</me>
      <me>\dfrac{1}{2}~~\text{of}~~32 = 16,~~~~~~~~~~\text{so}~~\dfrac{1}{2}=\dfrac{16}{32}</me>
      <me>\dfrac{3}{4}~~\text{of}~~32 = 3 \times 8 = 24,~~~~\text{so}~~\dfrac{3}{4}=\dfrac{24}{32}</me></p>
    
    <p>Now that we have written the benchmark fractions with the appropriate denominator, we can compare our fraction from part (a). We see that the fraction <m>\dfrac{9}{32}</m> is slightly more than <m>\dfrac{1}{4}</m> of the class.</p></li>
  </ol></solution></example>

  <note><p>In part (b) of the previous Example, do you see why
      <me>\dfrac{3}{4}~~\text{of}~~~~~32 = 3 \times 8 ?</me></p></note>

  <p> We can use a number line to compare fractions. Here are the fractions from the previous Example shown on a number line.
    <image source="comparenumberline.png" width="70%"><description>number line</description></image></p>

  <exercise><p>One yard is equal to 36 inches. <ol marker="a">
      <li><p>Compute the benchmark fractions with denominator 36.
        
        <me>\dfrac{1}{4}=~~~~~~~~~~ \dfrac{1}{2}=~~~~~~~~~~ \dfrac{3}{4}=~~~~~~~~~~</me></p></li>
      
